It was reported to me some time ago, that you had goodnaturedly declared you would like to “go on” in the Play,<note><hi rend="italic">The Frozen Deep</hi> by Wilkie Collins; performed in Jan 57 at Tavistock House: see Pilgrim <hi rend="italic">Letters</hi> 8.</note> for the fun of being in it. If this should be really so, and you do not object to become a Mute Seaman,<note>As one of the crews of the <hi rend="italic">Sea Mew and Wanderer</hi>, iced-in in the Arctic Regions, in Act II: see also <hi rend="italic">To</hi> Jones, 12 June.</note> “an eligible opportunity now offers”.<note>Imitating newspaper advertisements, for vacancies in clerical and professional employment.</note> A Seaman is summoned to Sheffield,<note>Edward Hogarth, Catherine’s youngest brother, due to play Bateson; employed in a business house in Sheffield threatened by failure: <hi rend="italic">To</hi> Thomas Hankey, 11 Dec 57, Pilgrim <hi rend="italic">Letters</hi> 8, p. 491.</note> and another Seaman (the speechless one) is ill.<note> Unidentified </note> We rehearse tonight at 1⁄4 before 8, for the last time before the Dress Rehearsal on Monday.
